{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1772048183,"nonce":"Ksi+iHxnGwa8X4DMmDhqNjndMgg=","message":"[GitHub comment by i-m-mll on 2026-02-21T23:42:05Z]\n\n## Update: MJXPlant as a continuous dynamical system (no discrete path needed)\n\n`mjx.forward(model, data)` computes forward dynamics (accelerations) without integrating. This means MJXPlant can expose a standard `vector_field()`:\n\n```python\ndef vector_field(t, state, input):\n    data = reconstruct_mjx_data(state)\n    data = data.replace(ctrl=input)\n    data = mjx.forward(self.mjx_model, data)\n    return (data.qvel, data.qacc)  # dqpos/dt, dqvel/dt\n```\n\nDiffrax handles integration — Euler (matching MuJoCo default), adaptive Tsit5, or anything else. No need for a separate discrete execution path. MJXPlant becomes a regular `AbstractDynamicalSystem` that works with existing `TaskTrainer`, Graph runner, and backprop.\n\nFor RL training, use `Euler(step_size=dt)` via Diffrax — functionally identical to `mjx.step()` but within the continuous framework.\n\nCaveat: this works well for biomechanical chains (no complex contacts). Contact-heavy scenarios would need careful treatment of acceleration discontinuities.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}